<p>At first, nothing looked out of the ordinary; attack and defense had a positive relationship and as they both increased, so did the experience yielded. This makes sense because as the game progresses, the Pokémon get stronger (their stats increase), which means the player is rewarded more significantly for defeating them (their base experience increases). Then I noticed something odd:</p>
<div class="cell">
<div class="cell-output-display">
<div>
<figure class="figure">
<p><img src="https://your-website-url.example.com/posts/blog_post_1/index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png" class="img-fluid figure-img" width="672"></p>
</figure>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A very dark dot (circled above) indicating a Pokémon with very high base experience close to the minimum values for defense and attack. This was very intriguing to me, as it is odd that a Pokémon that does not deal significant damage or lower received damage would be considered such a difficult opponent to net so much experience.</p>
<p>Upon further investigation, I found that this Pokémon is Blissey, a normal type Pokémon introduced in the second generation of the Pokémon games that is always female.</p>
